'''Herbert Dwight Smith''' (February 10, 1926 - July 1, 2011) was a longtime lawyer in [[Alva, Oklahoma]]. He was born on the Smith farm East of [[Alva, Oklahoma|Alva]], in the area known as <U+201C>Little Potsdam<U+201D>. His parents, Raymond Robert Smith and Esther Margaret Coulter Smith welcomed their second son on February 10, 1926.

==Early life==

Herbert D. Smith was born on February 10, 1926 to Raymond Robert Smith and Esther Margaret Coulter Smith. He became a member of the Alva Presbyterian Church at an early age.
Herb helped with the farming, which included working with a garden, orchard and dairy, plus assisting with wheat harvest in Oklahoma and Texas. Most of all after the death of his brother, Dean, in [[World War II]] and his return, he felt more responsibility for his parents and still helped with farming, etc.

==Education==

Smith graduated from Alva High School and was a member of the [[National Honor Society]] in [[1943]] and attended [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]] briefly, before joining the [[U.S. Army]].
The Army provided some education at [[Baylor University]], but eventually he was sent overseas to [[Germany]].
After being sent to Fitzsimmons Hospital, he returned to his home and enrolled at the [[University of Oklahoma]]. He served on the [[Student Senate]] and obtained his [[Chemical Engineering]] degree in 1950. That same year he was made homeless by the Bachelor Officer's Quarters fire. He then returned to Alva and assisted his father with farming, eventually forming his own harvesting operation traveling to various states, but home always looked the best.
Herb became interested in law and enrolled at O.U. in the [[School of Law]] in the Fall of 1955.

==War Experience==

Herbert D. Smith was a [[corporal]] in the Infantry Co. G 232nd Inf. 42nd Div. WWII. Smith was a runner for his company commander and was sent to survey the base's surrounding land. One day, he went out to survey the land and saw that German troops were coming. He informed his company commander of the enemy troops, but the commander said that they could not leave their base. He was captured in the [[Black Forest]] by the Germans and confined to [[Stalag IV-B|Stalag No. IV-B]] for 108 days. He was only served cabbage and a small ration of sugar. Prisoners had to sleep with their knees up to their chests because there was not enough space to lay out flat. They were also only allowed one uniform for their entire stay at the camp. Smith said that his uniform was so dirty that he could take his fingernail and scrape the dirt off of it. He was liberated by the Russians and returned home. His [[Honorable Discharge]] states he received the following Decorations and Citations: [[European-African-Middle Eastern Campaign Medal]], [[American Theater Medal]], [[World War II Victory Medal]], and [[Good Conduct Medal]]. In November, 1988, he received his [[Prisoner of War Medal]]. His battles and campaigns were Rhineland (GO 40 WD45) Central Europe (G0 40 WD45).

==Political career==

Smith was elected to the [[Oklahoma House of Representatives]] in [[1954]] on the [[Democratic]] ticket and served one term serving on the Enrolling and & Engrossing Bills Committee as Co-Chair. Herb passed the Oklahoma Bar and set up his law practice in July 1958. He was a member of the Oklahoma Bar Association and the [[American Bar Association]] and has served as Acting [[County Attorney]], Acting [[County Judge]] and Alva [[City Attorney]].

==Acting career==

He received the [[Best Actor Award]] in 1974 for his role as [[Elwood P. Dowd]] in ''[[Harvey (play)|Harvey]]''. There were several return performances as Charles Condamin in ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'', plus roles in ''[[Teahouse of the August Moon]]'', ''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'', and ''[[South Pacific (musical)|South Pacific]]'' to name a few. He was a quick study and had a <U+201C>razor sharp<U+201D> memory.

==Membership==

He served as [[deacon]] and [[elder]] for the [[Presbyterian Church]] and served as Building Chairman for the new Presbyterian Church dedicated May 4, 1965.
He has served as [[Worshipful Master]] of the [[Masonic Lodge]], Rainbow Dad for the [[Rainbow Girls]] and Advisor for the DeMolays. He is Past Commander of the [[American Legion]], a past member of the Alva Planning Commission and a past president of the Alva School Board and a member of [[Elks]] and [[Kiwanis]].

==Family Life==

He was engaged to Gerree Coley and they were married in the [[First Methodist Church]] in [[Hollis, Oklahoma|Hollis]], Oklahoma on November 24, 1955, Thanksgiving Day. Gerree Smith served as his first legal secretary.

He was <U+201C>Superman<U+201D> to his three children: Anita Lynn, Herbert Dean and Lisa Coley. The family never had a set of encyclopedia because he could answer any of their questions. He was always teaching his children and others. He was a wonderful Sunday School teacher for the Men's class and the Couple's class. When grandchildren arrived he was certain they needed to know about the '[[Declination#Sun|declination of the sun]]'. He loved his grandchildren, Megan, Bryan and Asia and Bryan's wife, Linnea and has become very fond of his son-in-law Ed and Ed's cooking.

==Interests==

Playing bridge and pitch were enjoyable with club members, also the [[Daily Oklahoman]]'s crossword puzzles, movies and comic strips helped make things a little more fun and interesting. He loved a challenge. Recently, his niece, Leslie, asked him to write a story about his father for her nephew, Ray, as a Christmas present in 2010. Eventually, he got everything written down and sent to her for Ray's enjoyment. He also was asked to go with certain local pilots and navigate for them. He had obtained a [[pilot's license]] himself in early years. Herb and Gerree traveled to [[London, England|London]] for Theatre Tours offered by [[Lawton, Oklahoma|Lawton]] Theatre group. Tourists asked Herb for directions in London.

==Awards==

In 2008, Herb received his 50 year pin from the Oklahoma Bar Association with [[Woods County]] Law Wives hosting the reception at County Court House. Judge Dean Linder made the presentation.

==Illness and Death==

Herbert D. Smith battled with [[Parkinson's disease]] for the last few years of his life. In May 2011, he was taken to Share Hospital in Alva, Oklahoma for [[cellulitis]], a common skin infection caused by bacteria. Other problems arose while he was there. On June 20, 2011, he was driven to [http://www.stmarysregional.com/Home St. Mary's] in [[Enid, Oklahoma]]. He had surgery the next day for [http://digestive.niddk.nih.gov/ddiseases/pubs/intestinaladhesions/ adhesions] in his intestines and was moved to the [[Intensive Care Unit]] (ICU) for ten days. Smith passed away on July 1, 2011.

